@Comment Positive selection on a new mutant allele can increase the frequencies of closely linked alleles (through
@Comment hitchhiking), as well as create linkage disequilibrium between them. Because this disequilibrium is induced
@Comment by the selected allele, one may be able to identify loci under selection by measuring the influence of a
@Comment candidate locus on pairwise disequilibrium values at nearby loci. The constrained disequilibrium values
@Comment (CDV) method approaches this problem by examining differences in pairwise disequilibrium values, which
@Comment have been normalized for two- and three-locus systems, respectively. We have investigated in detail the
@Comment reliability of inferences based on CDV, using simulation and analytical methods. Our main results are (i)
@Comment in some circumstances, CDV may not distinguish well between a selected locus and a neighboring neutral
@Comment locus, but (ii) CDV seldom indicates "selection" in neutral haplotypes with moderate to large 4Nc. We
@Comment conclude that, although the CDV method does not appear to precisely locate selected alleles, it can be
@Comment used to screen for regions in which hitchhiking is a plausible hypothesis.

